1. Maximum Cost of Permuted Array

Description

You are given two arrays A and B which consist of N positive integers each.

It is given that the cost of A is defined as the total number of indices where A[i] > B[i] for all 0 \le i < N. You can permute A as you want.

Find the maximum possible cost of A.

Function Description

Complete the maximumCost function in the editor below. It has the following parameter(s):

N (INTEGER): The number of elements in arrays A and B.

A (INTEGER ARRAY): The array A consisting of N positive integers.

B (INTEGER ARRAY): The array B consisting of N positive integers.

Return:
The function must return an INTEGER denoting the maximum possible cost of A.

Constraints

1 <= N <= 50000

1 <= A[i] <= 100000

1 <= B[i] <= 100000

Sample Testcases

Testcase 1

Input:

N = 1

A = [2]

B = [1]

Output: 1

Description: A and B both have one element and A > B at index 0. Hence, the output is 1.

Testcase 2

Input:

N = 3

A = [3, 1, 2]

B = [2, 3, 1]

Output: 2

Description: Here, N=3, A=[3,1,2] and B=[2,3,1]. Here, the cost will be 2. (If A is permuted, e.g., to [3, 2, 1], the cost is 2. If permuted to [2, 3, 1], cost is 1. The maximum is 2).

Testcase 3

Input:

N = 5

A = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]

B = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

Output: (Not explicitly stated, but implies 4)

Description: N=5, A=[5,4,3,2,1] and B=[1,2,3,4,5]. A can be permuted to [2,3,5,4,1] to maximize the cost.

A[0]=2 > B[0]=1 (Cost=1)

A[1]=3 > B[1]=2 (Cost=2)

A[2]=5 > B[2]=3 (Cost=3)

A[3]=4 > B[3]=4 (No cost)

A[4]=1 > B[4]=5 (No cost)

Self-correction from PDF description: The permutation [2, 3, 5, 4, 1] gives a cost of 3. A better permutation [5, 4, 3, 2, 1] (no permutation) gives a cost of 2. A permutation of [2, 3, 4, 5, 1] gives a cost of 4.